Just as a point of clarity, Gremlin isn't based on Groovy anymore and hasn't been for a long time. The Gremlin Console is Groovy-based though so you might see examples that are Groovy-oriented. You can write pure Gremlin natively in many programming languages.

TBH while I initially found cypher much more intuitive, once I learned more about functional programming it changed my understanding of Gremlin and how to leverage it. Not sure cypher can be as fast (assuming you have well-crafted gremlin queries). I don't care for Groovy tho!

that's fine and maybe more will adopt it. i'm merely pointing out that Gremlin is not an obscure experiment in the graphdb world that is straining to find traction. hopefully you can concede that much @maxdemarzi
Plenty of DBs use Cypher. See https://www. opencypher.org/projects . Checkout @memgraphdb for example: https:// memgraph.com/docs/open-cyph er/ …
